<subSubSection id="C311AFCBFF9FBD49FF2EFC6288F5FA52" pageId="8" pageNumber="1557" type="description">
<paragraph id="8BB4FC40FF9FBD49FF2EFC628B30FB88" blockId="8.[178,1086,914,1053]" pageId="8" pageNumber="1557">
Comment: The only previously known specimen is a single female 
<typeStatus id="54B042E2FF9FBD49FC29FC628D06FC32" box="[949,1028,914,935]" pageId="8" pageNumber="1557">syntype</typeStatus>
from 
<collectingRegion id="49CF32A2FF9FBD49FF2EFC5F89F5FC50" box="[178,247,943,965]" country="India" name="Assam" pageId="8" pageNumber="1557">Assam</collectingRegion>
deposited in the Cameron collection. Except for the slightly darker pronotum, the above male is externally similar to the 
<typeStatus id="54B042E2FF9FBD49FDD3FC3D8BA2FC77" box="[591,672,973,994]" pageId="8" pageNumber="1557">syntype</typeStatus>
, suggesting that it is conspecific. For a description and illustrations of the 
<typeStatus id="54B042E2FF9FBD49FD88FC1A8B61FC6A" box="[532,611,1002,1023]" pageId="8" pageNumber="1557">syntype</typeStatus>
see 
<bibRefCitation id="EF9A81B1FF9FBD49FD0CFC198A37FC6A" author="ASSING V" box="[656,821,1001,1023]" journalOrPublisher="Beitrage zur Entomologie, Keltern" pageId="8" pageNumber="1557" pagination="89 - 148" part="61" refId="ref3466" refString="ASSING V. (2011 a): A revision of the genus Neosclerus CAMERON (Coleoptera: Staphylinidae: Paederinae). - Beitrage zur Entomologie, Keltern 61 (1): 89 - 148." title="A revision of the genus Neosclerus CAMERON (Coleoptera: Staphylinidae: Paederinae)" type="journal article" year="2011">ASSING (2011a)</bibRefCitation>
. The previously unknown male sexual characters are as follows:
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BB4FC40FF9FBD49FF5BFBDD887CFB41" blockId="8.[178,1086,1068,1236]" pageId="8" pageNumber="1557">
: sternite VII (
<figureCitation id="1330E0C5FF9FBD49FEC6FBDC88A7FBD7" box="[346,421,1068,1090]" captionStart="Figs 17-21" captionStartId="9.[178,218,1270,1290]" captionTargetBox="[189,1082,221,1253]" captionTargetId="figure-76@9.[178,1085,212,1259]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="Figs 17-21: Neosclerus obscurus nov.sp. (Fig. 17) and N. assamensis (CAMERON) (Figs 18-21): (17, 19) male sternite VIII; (18) male sternite VII; (20-21) aedeagus in lateral and in ventral view. Scale bars: 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5302512" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5302512/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="1557">Fig. 18</figureCitation>
) as long as broad, posteriorly with cluster of modified short and stout black setae; posterior margin weakly concave in the middle; sternite VIII (
<figureCitation id="1330E0C5FF9FBD49FC77FBB98D34FBCA" box="[1003,1078,1097,1119]" captionStart="Figs 17-21" captionStartId="9.[178,218,1270,1290]" captionTargetBox="[189,1082,221,1253]" captionTargetId="figure-76@9.[178,1085,212,1259]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="Figs 17-21: Neosclerus obscurus nov.sp. (Fig. 17) and N. assamensis (CAMERON) (Figs 18-21): (17, 19) male sternite VIII; (18) male sternite VII; (20-21) aedeagus in lateral and in ventral view. Scale bars: 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5302512" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5302512/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="1557">Fig. 19</figureCitation>
) oblong, anteriorly with median cluster of short dark setae, median portion in posterior half without setae, posterior excision large and V-shaped; aedeagus (
<figureCitation id="1330E0C5FF9FBD49FC10FB748AFDFB0F" box="[908,1023,1156,1178]" captionStart="Figs 17-21" captionStartId="9.[178,218,1270,1290]" captionTargetBox="[189,1082,221,1253]" captionTargetId="figure-76@9.[178,1085,212,1259]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="Figs 17-21: Neosclerus obscurus nov.sp. (Fig. 17) and N. assamensis (CAMERON) (Figs 18-21): (17, 19) male sternite VIII; (18) male sternite VII; (20-21) aedeagus in lateral and in ventral view. Scale bars: 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5302512" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5302512/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="1557">Figs 20-21</figureCitation>
) 
<quantity id="4CF351A5FF9FBD49FB8DFB7489DBFB22" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.4" pageId="8" pageNumber="1557" unit="mm" value="0.54">0.54 mm</quantity>
long, ventral process straight, apically acute, and in the middle with ventral dent best seen in lateral view.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BB4FC40FF9FBD49FF2EFB1488F5FA52" blockId="8.[178,1086,1252,1479]" pageId="8" pageNumber="1557">
Based on the male sexual characters (shapes and chaeotaxy of sternites VII and VIII; morphology of the aedeagus), 
<taxonomicName id="4C0B87C3FF9FBD49FE6FFAF28B87FA82" baseAuthorityName="CAMERON" baseAuthorityYear="1931" box="[499,645,1282,1303]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Neosclerus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="1557" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="assamensis">
<emphasis id="B97F2052FF9FBD49FE6FFAF28B87FA82" box="[499,645,1282,1303]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="1557">N. assamensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is most closely related to 
<taxonomicName id="4C0B87C3FF9FBD49FC3CFAF28D35FA82" box="[928,1079,1281,1303]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Neosclerus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="1557" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="brevipennis">
<emphasis id="B97F2052FF9FBD49FC3CFAF28D35FA82" box="[928,1079,1281,1303]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="1557">N. brevipennis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, from which it differs by the longer elytra, paler coloration of the pronotum and the elytra, the shape and chaetotaxy of the male sternite VII (posterior concavity smaller; presence of cluster of stout black setae posteriorly), the shape and chaetotaxy of the male sternite VIII (posterior excision larger and deeper, anteriorly less strongly elevated and with more distinct cluster of setae), and by the slightly different shape of the aedeagus (ventral process straight in lateral view).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C311AFCBFF9FBD49FF2EFA268BEFFA79" box="[178,749,1494,1516]" pageId="8" pageNumber="1557" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="8BB4FC40FF9FBD49FF2EFA268BEFFA79" blockId="8.[178,749,1494,1516]" box="[178,749,1494,1516]" pageId="8" pageNumber="1557">
The currently known distribution is illustrated in 
<figureCitation id="1330E0C5FF9FBD49FD39FA278BEBFA79" box="[677,745,1494,1516]" captionStart="Map 3" captionStartId="5.[178,223,1463,1483]" captionTargetBox="[178,1085,643,1450]" captionTargetId="figure-250@5.[178,1085,642,1450]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="Map 3: Distributions of Neosclerus dupleseriatus ASSING (circles), N. brevipennis (CAMERON) (filled triangles: male-based records; open triangle: female-based record), N. assamensis (CAMERON) (diamonds), and N. obscurus nov.sp. (star)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5302508" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5302508/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="1557">Map 3</figureCitation>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
